I am a historian with the Navy History and Heritage Command (NHHC) in Washington DC. I am currently researching and writing a ship's history of USS Bunker Hill (CV-17) for inclusion in our Dictionary of Naval Fighting Ships (DANFS). I will unfortunately never be able to tell the story of every brave sailor, airman, and Marine that served aboard, but if anyone has any information they can provide me such as a diary, journal, letter, or other primary source material, especially concerning the sinking of the battleship Yamato and/or the kamikaze strikes and aftermath, I would be very grateful. Veterans especially, I am hoping to hear from you about your experiences onboard Bunker Hill! Please contact me at guy.nasuti@navy.mil or guy.nasuti@gmail.com. </div><div id='commentItem93' class='commentItem' style='background-color: #f0f0f0'>93. <span style='font-style: italic;'>Jackie Evans</span> says:<br /><small>27 Jul 2016 07:42:31 PM</small><br /><br />I have information on Radioman, Barney Garland Neal, killed on the USS Bunker Hill in 1945 that includes photos, his Purple Heart, sympathy letters from President Truman and Cpt. H.L. Meadow, Commander, Cemetery information, birth dates/city.  As the Uncle I never met but is the reason I joined the Navy, I would love to get his name and particulars added.  Would someone please contact me for this information?  Thank you!</div><div id='commentItem94' class='commentItem' style='background-color: '>94. <span style='font-style: italic;'>Bruce King</span> says:<br /><small>6 Aug 2016 06:03:51 PM</small><br /><br />My Dad served aboard when the ship was commissioned and sailed to the Pacific. He left the ship when she returned for maintenance and repair in November of 1944.His name was John Edward King ,Fire Controlman First Class.The Greatest Generation!! GOD BLESS OUR TROOPS
